cross-border mobility of remittance financial flows against the relative confines of state bounded bodies. In this contradiction Ivan V. Small reveals a creative space for emergent imaginaries that disrupt local structures and scales of desire, labor and expectation. Furthermore, the particular characteristics of remittance channels and mediums in a global economy, including transnational mobility and exchangeable value, affect and reflect the relations, aspirations, and orientations of the exchange participants. Small traces a genealogy of how this phenomenon has shifted through changing remittance forms and transfer infrastructures, from material and black market to formal bank and money services. Transformations in the affective and institutional relations among givers, receivers, and remittance facilitators accompany each of these shifts, illustrating that the socio-cultural work of remittances extends far beyond the formal economic realm they are usually consigned to.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aEmigrant remittanceszVietnam. 0aFamiliesxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aFamiliesxEconomic aspectszVietnam. 0aImmigrantsxFamily relationshipszUnited States. 0aImmigrantsxFamily relationshipszVietnam. 0aMoneyxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aMoneyxSocial aspectszVietnam. 0aTransnationalismxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aTransnationalismxSocial aspectszVietnam. 0aVietnamesezUnited StatesxEconomic conditions. 0aVietnamesezUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies. 4aGeneral Economics. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  adiasporic remittance economies, transnational kinship networks, Long distance international gift exchanges, neoliberal political economy, socio-cultural work of remittances, migration.08iTitle is part o